### Which @angular/* package(s) are the source of the bug?

core

### Is this a regression?

Yes

### Description

Please take a look at this example first.

```typescript
import { Component, OnInit, WritableSignal, signal } from '@angular/core';
import { bootstrapApplication } from '@angular/platform-browser';

interface Test {
  name: string;
  value?: string;
}

@Component({
  selector: 'app-root',
  template: `
    <span>Name: {{ mySignal().name }}</span>
    <br>
    @if (mySignal().value === undefined) {
      <span>No value</span>
    }
    @else {
      <span>Value: {{ mySignal().value }}</span>
    }
  `,
})
export class App implements OnInit {
  mySignal: WritableSignal<Test> = signal({ name: 'Name', value: undefined });

  public ngOnInit(): void {
    this.loadValue();
  }

  private async loadValue(): Promise<void> {
    const data = this.mySignal();
    await new Promise((r) => setTimeout(r, 2000));
    data.value = 'Value';
    this.mySignal.set(data);
  }
}

bootstrapApplication(App);
```

In the example we have the signal `mySignal`. This signal is a object from the interface `Test`. Test has the key named `value` which is represents data we need to load. Is is initialised with `undefined`.

We have the async function `laodData()` which called from `ngOnInit` and is responsible for loading the data. It does the following:
1. Read the current value of `mySignal`
2. Wait 2 seconds (represents an API call)
3. Set the value to `Value`
4. Update the signal

So after tow seconds the value should be displayed. However, Angular fails to detect that the Signal has changed.

A workaround is replacing `this.mySignal.set(data)` with `this.mySignal.set(window.structuredClone(data))`.

